item.value: 2. Before running any task, the lock is acquired to prevent other pool interrupts while the task is executing, and then we ensure that unless pool is stopping, this thread does not have its interrupt set.

We may start out with an initial task, in which case we don't need to get the first one. Otherwise, as long as pool is running, we get tasks from getTask. If it returns null then the worker exits due to changed pool state or configuration parameters. Other exits result from exception throws in external code, in which case completedAbruptly holds, which usually leads processWorkerExit to replace this thread.

So we recheck state and if necessary roll back the enqueuing if stopped, or start a new thread if there are none.

If a task can be successfully queued, then we still need to double-check whether we should have added a thread (because existing ones died since last checking) or that the pool shut down since entry into this method
